T1  - Is Canadian carbon pricing here to stay? The outlook after 14 elections
AN  - 2357240728
AB  - When Justin Trudeau met Canada's premiers to negotiate a national carbon price in 2016, there had arguably never been a better time to do so. With Liberal governments in most provinces, negotiations concluded quite quickly, with pledges from 11 of the 13 premiers to implement a carbon price as part of the Pan-Canadian Framework on Climate Change (PCF). On the face of it, implementing these prices should have been straightforward: the carbon price (starting at $20/tonne in 2018, and rising to $50/tonne in 2022) was decidedly modest, and unlikely to have any significant macroeconomic impact: pulling $7 billion per year out of a 1.8 trillion-dollar economy is tantamount to a rounding error, and the plan involved provided rebates that would actually improve the economic standing of more than 70% of Canadian households. The reality, however, was the Canada's carbon price was destined to be extremely fragile, as these 11 pro-climate governments would be forced to defend this new 'tax' in their subsequent elections. Indeed, while Canadians were unlikely to feel any negative effects of the carbon price directly, they would undoubtedly learn about it in the scariest possible terms from conservative politicians and right-wing media outlets, who indicated early on their intention to take advantage of the public's poor grasp of carbon pricing to undermine the policy and gain electoral advantage. This was precisely the tactic employed so skilfully in the 2008 federal election, when Stephen Harper's Conservative government engaged in a relentless scare campaign around carbon taxes to discredit his opposition. It was also deftly employed by Tony Abbott in the 2013 federal election in Australia - arguably the polity most analogous to Canada's - after which he managed to fully overturn the country's existing carbon price. Indeed, for many observers, the true durability of Canadian carbon pricing was always going to be determined by the battle for public opinion that would ensue in the years following the signing of the PCF. How, then, had this battle played out? To what extent were conservative forces across Canada able to capitalize successfully on anti-carbon tax...
