T1  - "Roots" or the virtualities of racial imaginaries in Puerto Rico and the diaspora
AN  - 748323907
AB  - This essay analyzes representations and imaginaries of blackness in contemporary Puerto Rico, by focusing on the debates raised by "Raíces"/(Roots) (2001), the Banco Popular video special about traditional Afro-Puerto Rican rhythms of bomba and plena. These debates divided public opinion in Puerto Rico and included members of academia, musicologists, bomba and plena groups, and the San Antón (Ponce) community residents. They refer to the ways Puerto Ricans "speak the unspoken," that is, the ways Puerto Ricans talk about race and its intersectionalities on the island and in the diaspora. Authenticity claims, particularly as to why bomba and plena appeared alongside reggae or hip-hop, are discussed in terms of four important elements: (1) the musical, cultural and social discourses of blackness in Puerto Rico and the ways they are represented in the media; (2) the complex dialogues between Puerto Rican definitions of blackness/whiteness and the African Diaspora; (3) forms of racialization of the Puerto Rican diaspora; and (4) the ways roots are also routes that articulate an understanding of blackness, race, and racialization in contemporary Caribbean/US global circuits. [PUBLICATION ABSTRACT]
